{{Nihongo|'''Mitsuhide Hirasawa'''|<U+5E73><U+6FA4> <U+5149><U+79C0>|Hirasawa Mitsuhide|born 27 March 1982 in [[Sapporo, Hokkaido]]}}<ref name="njpw"/> also known by his [[ring name]] {{Nihongo|'''Hideo Saito'''|<U+30D2><U+30C7><U+30AA><U+30FB><U+30B5><U+30A4><U+30C8><U+30FC>|Saito Hideo}}, is a Japanese [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], currently signed with [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]].<ref name="njpw">[http://www.njpw.co.jp/data/detail_profile.php?f=709 New Japan Pro Wrestling profile]. Retrieved 24 July 2011. {{ja icon}}</ref>

==Professional wrestling career==
===New Japan Pro Wrestling (2006<U+2013>present)===
Hirasawa originally debuted for [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] on 28 January 2006.<ref name="njpw"/> In the fall of 2009, Hirasawa joined [[Yuji Nagata]]'s new [[Blue Justice|Blue Justice Army]] along with [[Wataru Inoue]] and [[Junji Hirata|Super Strong Machine]]. After embarking on an extended tour of Puerto Rican [[World Wrestling Council]] (WWC) in September 2010, Hirasawa adopted the new ring name Hideo Saito as a tribute to [[Masa Saito]] and [[Hideo Nomo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=2146|title=Hirasawa wins title in Puerto Rico!|date=28 September 2010|accessdate=18 May 2011|work=Strong Style Spirit}}</ref> In WWC Saito would win both the [[WWC Caribbean Heavyweight Championship]] and the [[WWC Puerto Rico Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name="njpw"/> In May 2011 Saito took part in New Japan's first tour of the United States. On 13 May in [[Rahway, New Jersey]], he entered the tournament to determine the first ever [[IWGP Intercontinental Championship|IWGP Intercontinental Champion]], losing to [[Yujiro Takahashi]] in his first round match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1305392240|title=5/13 New Japan Pro Wrestling Results: Rahway, NJ|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=14 May 2011|accessdate=15 May 2011|work=WrestleView}}</ref> Hirasawa returned to New Japan on 18 June, now going permanently by the Saito name, and turned on the Blue Justice Army and its leader Yuji Nagata, joining [[Chaos (professional wrestling)|CHAOS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=2912|title=(Results) New Japan, 6/18/11|work=Strong Style Spirit|date=18 June 2011|accessdate=18 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/news/detail.php?nid=5899|title=<U+4ECA><U+5E74><U+306E><U+300E>G1 CLIMAX<U+300F><U+51FA><U+5834>20<U+9078><U+624B><U+304C><U+6C7A><U+5B9A>!! <U+9234><U+6728><U+307F><U+306E><U+308B><U+3001><U+9AD8><U+5C71><U+5584><U+5EE3><U+3001><U+30E9><U+30FB><U+30BD><U+30F3><U+30D6><U+30E9><U+3082><U+51FA><U+5834>!!|work=[[New Japan Pro Wrestling]]|date=3 July 2011|accessdate=3 July 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref> In August, Saito took part in the [[G1 Climax#2011|2011 G1 Climax]], losing his first eight matches only to pick up his opening win on the final day of the tournament in a match against former mentor, Yuji Nagata.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result.php?e=322|title=<U+30D6><U+30B7><U+30ED><U+30FC><U+30C9> Presents G1 Climax XXI <U+FF5E>The Invincible Fighter<U+FF5E>|date=14 August 2011|work=[[New Japan Pro Wrestling]]|accessdate=14 August 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref> On 19 September, Nagata defeated his former prot<U+00E9>g<U+00E9> in a grudge match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=3169|title=(Results) New Japan, 9/19/11|work=Strong Style Spirit|date=19 September 2011|accessdate=19 September 2011}}</ref> Saito's erradic behaviour and poor match results eventually led to the rest of CHAOS kicking him out of the stable on 4 December 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=3294|title=(Results) New Japan, 12/4/11|work=Strong Style Spirit|date=4 December 2011|accessdate=5 December 2011}}</ref> After his exhile from CHAOS, Saito developed an alter-ego called '''Captain New Japan''', dressed in a variation of the [[Captain America]] costume, complete with a shield.<ref name=WKVIResultsWON>{{cite web|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/more/more-top-stories/96-wwe/23632-new-japan-tokyo-dome-results-1-4|title=New Japan Tokyo Dome results 1-4|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=4 January 2012|accessdate=4 January 2012|work=[[Dave Meltzer#Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/match/detail_result_game.php?e=470&c=3728|title=NJPW 40th anniversary Tour. <U+30EC><U+30C3><U+30B9><U+30EB><U+30AD><U+30F3><U+30B0><U+30C0><U+30E0><U+2165> in <U+6771><U+4EAC><U+30C9><U+30FC><U+30E0>|accessdate=5 January 2012|work=[[New Japan Pro Wrestling]]|language=Japanese}}</ref>

